metadata.name: Celestial Rings: Algorithmic Study #59
metadata.description:
This is an exploration to create an abstract artwork using fields and growth rings and their interaction with each other. Each of the mints can have several central rings up to 14 and the rings interact with each other to form a larger structure. The structure of the rings can be uniform or rotating, with mixed colors or mono colors. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

Open it in live view and press ’s’ to save image with high resolution.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #39
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pewén, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the Wünelfe star, and the staggered cross Ngümin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

–

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

Patricio Isaías, September 2022

CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 License

metadata.name: Color Study II #1
metadata.description:
Color Study II builds on work done in Color Study I to create a generalized color model. Though unlike the simple graphics of Color Study I, the goal for this project was a much more visually rich outcome. The composition builds that richness through layering and texture.  Initially, 100 images are algorithmically created and stored in an array.  The script uses an analogous color scheme, and each set of images is based on a randomly selected primary hue.  As shapes are drawn, the saturation, brightness, and transparency of the hues in the palette are randomly altered. Other random elements include the number, type, size, and placement of shapes, as well as the drawing orientation.

Once the set of images is completed and stored, a selection of the images are randomly chosen for layering.  Blend modes are varied as each is added to the canvas. The result is a complex collage celebrating the simply joy of color.

Created by Wanda Oliver (wandaoliver.tez) in Sept., 2022.
This work is licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

Press [S] in live mode to save with high-resolution.
